@page "/ControlSamples/Theming"
@using BlazorWebFormsComponents.Theming

<PageTitle>Theming - Skins &amp; Themes PoC</PageTitle>

<h2>Skins &amp; Themes PoC</h2>

<p>This sample demonstrates the Skins &amp; Themes system, which emulates ASP.NET Web Forms'
<code>.skin</code> file behavior using Blazor's cascading values.</p>

<h3>Themed Components</h3>
<p>These components receive their visual properties from a <code>ThemeConfiguration</code>
provided via <code>ThemeProvider</code>.</p>

<ThemeProvider Theme="@SampleTheme">
    <h4>Default Skin</h4>
    <p>Button and Label with default theme skin applied:</p>
    <Button Text="Themed Button" />
    <br /><br />
    <Label Text="Themed Label" />

    <h4>Named Skin (SkinID)</h4>
    <p>Button with <code>SkinID="Danger"</code> gets a different skin:</p>
    <Button Text="Danger Button" SkinID="Danger" />

    <h4>EnableTheming = false</h4>
    <p>This button opts out of theming entirely:</p>
    <Button Text="Unthemed Button" EnableTheming="false" />
</ThemeProvider>

<h3>Without ThemeProvider</h3>
<p>Components outside the <code>ThemeProvider</code> keep their default appearance:</p>
<Button Text="No Theme Button" />

<hr />

<h2>Migration Guide &mdash; Before &amp; After</h2>

<p>The Skins &amp; Themes system maps directly from ASP.NET Web Forms concepts.
Here is a concrete example showing how to migrate themed controls.</p>

<h3>Before (Web Forms)</h3>

<pre><code>App_Themes/Corporate/controls.skin:

&lt;asp:Button runat="server"
    BackColor="#336699"
    ForeColor="White"
    Font-Names="Segoe UI"
    Font-Size="9pt"
    BorderStyle="None" /&gt;

&lt;asp:Button runat="server" SkinID="danger"
    BackColor="#CC3333"
    ForeColor="White"
    Font-Bold="True" /&gt;

web.config:
&lt;pages theme="Corporate" /&gt;

Products.aspx:
&lt;asp:Button ID="btnSave" runat="server" Text="Save" /&gt;
&lt;asp:Button ID="btnDelete" runat="server" Text="Delete" SkinID="danger" /&gt;</code></pre>

<h3>Migration Steps</h3>

<ol>
    <li>Create a <code>ThemeConfiguration</code> in C# matching your <code>.skin</code> file</li>
    <li>Wrap your app (or page) in a <code>ThemeProvider</code></li>
    <li>Remove <code>asp:</code> prefix and <code>runat="server"</code> from markup</li>
    <li>Keep <code>SkinID</code> attributes &mdash; they work the same way</li>
</ol>

<h3>After (Blazor)</h3>

<pre><code class="language-razor">@@* Program.cs or App.razor *@@
&lt;ThemeProvider Theme="@@corporateTheme"&gt;
    &lt;Router ... /&gt;
&lt;/ThemeProvider&gt;

@@* Products.razor — markup barely changes *@@
&lt;Button ID="btnSave" Text="Save" /&gt;
&lt;Button ID="btnDelete" Text="Delete" SkinID="danger" /&gt;</code></pre>

@code {
    private ThemeConfiguration SampleTheme;

    protected override void OnInitialized()
    {
        SampleTheme = new ThemeConfiguration();

        // Default Button skin — blue background with white text
        SampleTheme.AddSkin("Button", new ControlSkin
        {
            BackColor = WebColor.Blue,
            ForeColor = WebColor.White,
            CssClass = "themed-button"
        });

        // Named "Danger" Button skin — red background
        SampleTheme.AddSkin("Button", new ControlSkin
        {
            BackColor = WebColor.Red,
            ForeColor = WebColor.White,
            CssClass = "themed-button-danger"
        }, "Danger");

        // Default Label skin — bold navy text
        SampleTheme.AddSkin("Label", new ControlSkin
        {
            ForeColor = WebColor.Navy,
            Font = new FontInfo { Bold = true }
        });
    }
}
